summary:
The problem was a race condition in `app/counter.js` when incrementing the Redis counter. It read the current value, incremented it locally, and then wrote it back. When multiple requests did this concurrently, reads and writes interleaved causing lost increments.

To fix it, we need to change it to an atomic operation using Redis's `INCR` command. I've updated `app/counter.js` to change `incrementCounter` from:
```javascript
  // Read current value
  const current = await client.get(COUNTER_KEY);
  const value = parseInt(current || "0", 10);

  // Increment and write back
  const newValue = value + 1;
  await client.set(COUNTER_KEY, newValue.toString());
```
to:
```javascript
  // Atomically increment
  const newValue = await client.incr(COUNTER_KEY);
  const value = newValue - 1;
```

I've tested the fix and `test.sh` now completes successfully:
```
Firing 100 concurrent increments...
Expected: 100
Got:      100
PASS: Counter is correct
```
